commentBody:
@Stephen Guthartz

What are you doing in here?  Didn't I tell you to go outside despite the cold yesterday?

I'm afraid I'm going to have to make that a DIRECT ORDER.

@Dave K.
The Mini does have enough! Let's keep the Super Bowl theme in the Mini! Ugh, the thought of an entire Sunday full of football clues, not my first choice. I'm sure I've done one, though. 

Now Art Heist... there's a good Sunday theme.

@Michael

The puzzle Gods giveth and taketh - one day chicken, next day feathers. I'm glad to be sittin' at the table, with enough grit to fill em' if I'm lucky! üòâ

Happy solving, everyone.

@HeathieJ

A few years ago David C clued us in to the use of pear wood for musical instruments.  I think oboes were mentioned.

I happened to remember that since I have a couple of pear trees on my property.  Small, hard green fruit but the deer and dogs seem to like them.

@Steve L

I doubt that the Vikings are going to prevail.

Then again, I don't really care.  No Vikings fan can afford to care.

@HeathieJ

üòÜ

There are a surprising number of Green Bay fans here in the Twin Cities.  I guess that's inevitable for a sizable metropolitan area ten miles from the Wisconsin border.

@David G
Rule of thumb: The longer your explanation and the more background information and details you have to provide, the less likely you are to change anyone's understanding, let alone their views!
And yes, this applies to my posts too. But sometimes I forget.

@Whoa Nellie

I guess it only gets serious when it escalates to the refrigerator.

Or anywhere in the kitchen, I suppose.

@Francis
Holy cow, really? Ok that went far over my head. So I looked it up, and you're right. At the time of 15D I rationalized it with utopia is so ideal that it's the most ideal of all. Lol. 

@SP, yeah it was lost on me. I'm pretty well read for a scientist, but the operative phrase here is "for a scientist."

@Francis

There is though. Research shows physical activity, interacting with as many people as one can, as often as possible, and mental workouts all contribute to staving off age-related cognitive decline. My dad is slightly older than you. He does all those things and he's as sharp as ever. 

(Yes, for once my post is 100% legit, no joshing, no jabs)

@Andrzej

True, but a vigorous walk for me requires both a walking stick and frequent stops.

Not an excuse, I realize.  But I have to admit that fighting physical decline is more challenging than I thought it would be.

@Lavinia
@Nancy J.

I have not tried pilates.  I might need think about that.  My wife did the for a while, so maybe I'll start there.

I have tried swimming.  I've never been good at it, which I guess is actually a plus if one is looking for a quick cardio.  It's something my PCP has suggested.  

I tried it once recently, but realized I needed to hone my logistics skills on getting all the stuff into the bag that I need, and thinking through how I'll deal with being wet.  üòÄ  It feels like nothing is small potatoes any more.

Thanks you both so much for your very, very kind suggestions.  I appreciate it, cross my heart.

@Nancy J.

I think this forum is a million times better than AI (That's Artificial Intelligence, not someone who goes by a shortened "Allan"-- so, for example, no offense, AI From Pittsburg).

Just posit a conundrum, and the great advice comes rolling out like a slot machine paying off, something I've never experienced.

@Francis
Along the "Flowers for Algernon" lines, some people spend the first decade or two of their adult lives being the youngest person in the room and then, poof! One day, they're just an ordinary person. This may pass unnoticed, their accomplishments are no longer surprising but expected, and life toddles on, but an even worse shock awaits. Next time you look around the office/ factory floor/warehouse, you're the old veteran, capable of advice and reassurance but not innovation. 
Life is unremittingly shocking, even if/especially if you're paying attention. Why do think we get wrinkles?

@Francis

In the spirit of the Olympics:

Quando en Italia, mi chiamo Alfredo. üáÆüáπ

@Nemma
Congratulations on your new home.  We have lived in the same house for more than 50 years and can't imagine living anywhere else.

It's important not to start giving yourself a pass on doing things because of your age, but it will be important to have contacts and friends, so do get to know your neighbors. You are still a young woman, and putting yourself in the way of meeting people in person is better than an app.

@Francis
I was stuck for about 5 min on "finished but wrong" message.  I went through it across and down.  I checked all the O's to make sure I hadn't hit zero.  Still wrong.

Finally looked at the answer key..   KaBABS crossing TINMaN!!  AARRGGG!!!

@Matt

Well, I agree it was a pretty easy puzzle.

However, from what I've read, Sunday's are aimed to be Wednesday level cluing, so Tuesday level wouldn't be all that far off.

@Francis

Easiest Sunday I've (in my limited run) ever done.

Maybe by far.

@Jim Based on your post yesterday regarding the End key... what software do you use for writing music? I use PowerTab Editor, which creates both tablature and music charts. For lyrics, I use SongbookPro, but I don't write songs, I just destroy existing ones.
But I do transcribe quite a bit. I do that mainly for putting solos together. My biggest challenge was the sax and guitar solos for Angry Eyes. I start out with pencil and blank ledger paper and put the results on PT, then PDF it for sharing.
Thanks

@Paul  and @Karen
Interesting.  It is true our Spanish teachers/texts skewed toward Mexican (and Cuban) vocab/usage.   I noticed it a lot when Puerto Rican Spanish was in books I was reading.

My last yr of Spanish was taught by a Cuban refugee (middle-aged woman who had been wealthy and privileged.)  She insisted on Castilian pronunciation.

@Me.

I always imagine that the constructors throw hints our way for tricky crossings.

As I wondered whether to write in an a or an E, I reread the clue.  I thought the dual Dreyfuss/DeVito in the clue was a nudge that it should be MEN and not MaN.

@Lewis

Your analysis of a puzzle...

It's like I'm in 10th grade English again, when the smart people dissect an e.e. cummings poem before I can even stop wondering where all the capital letters are.

@SBK

Imagine one of your Francophone compatriots pronouncing those words aloud, and think of the difference between their final a‚Äôs and yours. They will, in fact, say cah-nah-DAH. You will say CAN-nuh-duh. And so it will be with all your unstressed vowels. 

As a native speaker, you don‚Äôt notice it. But compared to the pronunciation of someone who is dominant in another language, it becomes obvious. (In NY, I‚Äôd tell someone to think of a person whose native language was Spanish; it works the same.)

@Xword Junkie
So we can't clue 'pain' because some of us have neuralgia. We can't clue 'mourning' because some of us have lost loved ones. We can't clue 'abuse' because some of us have been abused.
It is impossible and, for me, wrong and unhealthy to ignore elements of reality. Au contraire! Better to try make these topics and experiences more discussable by hauling them out into daylight. Crosswords are a tiny part of public discourse but can contribute to this process.

@SBK

In general, I'm tired of "trigger warnings" and I think people need to grow a thicker skin and not expect that there won't be painful things to deal with when they go out into the world.

But you should note that @Xword Junkie isn't complaining about the word ACNE in the puzzle (we all surely know that it's been in the puzzle many times).  Rather X is complaining about the word-play that seems to be making a joke out of a serious medical condition.

@Seloegal

Is this your first NYT puzzle? Diacritic marks are never used in crossword entries, even when it means offensively misspelling Slavic names, say (this also in the clues)

But it's ok because it's in line with the style guide!

@LW

Also unfamiliar with the film, I had to decide between TINMAN and TINMEN. 

I took the inclusion of *two* actors in the clue to be an intentional hint: 1987 Dreyfuss/DeVito comedy

@Xword Junkie

Oh, good point! I didn't catch on to that hint, unfortunately. 


@LW

I said exactly the same to my partner just before cracking open the comments. He's more apt to know the films of those actors, so prior to voicing my gripe, I asked if he could name an 80's film starring them both ‚Äì to no avail. I thought it could use a better clue... but given the overall ease of this puzzle, I probably shouldn't grumble!

@Mean Old Lady
The sweetest swig I ever had was some WV moonshine. Crystal clear. I had been fasting for a couple of weeks at the time and that single swallow induced a transcendental experience.

Ah, the fearlessness of youth. It's a wonder I survived.

@Barry Ancona
Especially along the Mediterranean's coasts and surrounding nations -- where spelling depends on not only the sound of the words but also which language it filtered through on its way to you.

I prefer my baba very ghanooj. And don't even ask me to spell imam bayilde.

@Katie

Does everyone have one of those giant neck zits?

Yeah, St. Theresa was a lucky woman.

@Tammy in Toronto
Both 'loonie' and 'toonie' are familiar or vernacular names. Neither is an official name, at least according to the Royal Canadian Mint. They are officially referred to as "1-dollar coin" and "2-dollar coin". How blandly Canadian!

<a href="https://www.mint.ca/en/discover/canadian-circulation" target="_blank">https://www.mint.ca/en/discover/canadian-circulation</a>

@Shari Coats I agree. It wasn't the hardest crossword, but that's nothing to do with good/bad. The theme was simple but useful during the solve. My pet peeve is a theme that you only notice after solving. Not interested in constructors' ego trips. 
Plenty of interesting fill and clues here, lots of ways in when stuck, overall a nice puzzle experience.
Thanks Chloe!

@Steve L, I'm a veteran solver, at least four decades, closer to five. An easy puzzler doesn't detract from my enjoyment, especially one with a clever and fun theme. Maybe I'm an outlier; don't really know, don't really care. But I agree with Shari and Alex's attitudes. Live and let live. 

I understand your view perfectly; can you see the views of others?

(I'm neither hostile nor argumentative here; I enjoy your commentary on the regular. Today I just felt compelled to reply.)

@Peter C.

"...a self-selected group of highly interested, highly skilled solvers who represent only a fraction of the NY Times crossword solving community..." 

Which, lest we forget, is also what this group is ‚Äì those of us who comment on the crossword here on the Wordplay column. I think it takes a lot of hubris to say we somehow know what all those thousands of solvers care for in a puzzle!

@Francis, fair enough. 

I don't know anyone personally who counted Brady's Tampa victory as a New England win!

I grew up in CT, and after our college/grad school years in VA, NJ, and NY, ended up back in New England, where I've now lived for 30 years. The Pats are my home team, so Go Pats, dues be darned! üèàüèàüèà

@Sadie Sharkey
You did get the veiled capital in the clue for 15 D? 

Sorry if, as you say, you don't need an explanation, but I'm puzzled about what you consider "not good." I spent several moments thinking it was a superlative, and when I realized who it was referring to, it was the biggest Aha! of the puzzle for me.

@HeathieJ
I actually have more problems with shaded squares--I solve on a laptop PC, and when I click on an entry, the squares become a sky blue, with yellow on the square I'm currently entering. This overlays any shading, and makes it hard to see, especially in the middle of an entry.
I hear that in beta versions of the app, when you click on a highlighted square, a tiny hand will emerge from the screen, and whack you over the head with a mallet.

@Bill

The yellow and blue occur on the mobile web version, too. And it does become difficult to see any shading! 

But I'm with @HeathieJ, the circles are even worse for my aging eyes... With the shading, I can read it fairly well as long as it's not my current entry slot. With circles, it's hopeless in every case. And impossible in the teeny-tiny squares of a Sunday grid!

@Bill
My perception is that the puzzle had gotten a lot easier for the last few years and recently have had several that approached the typical Sundays many of us were accustomed to. Did you start solving during that easy period? 

If so, stick with it. I found the learning curve long, but very fun. But I do miss the days when I would spend a good two weeks on a Sunday puzzle, a little bit each night.
